Prioritise a canonical metric dictionary first: impact is highest because every dashboard, experiment readout, and target depends on consistent definitions; confidence is high because scope is bounded; effort is medium.
Second, formalise the decision-rights and escalation process for roadmap changes: impact is high because it reduces churn, hidden dependencies, and approval latency; confidence is medium-high; effort is low to medium.
Third, formalise experiment design and launch criteria: impact is high but more delayed because benefits depend on adoption by PM, design, data, and engineering; confidence is medium; effort is medium-high.
Overall order is metric dictionary, then decision-rights, then experiment criteria.
That sequence maximises near-term leverage by fixing the language of performance first, then the operating model, then the learning loop.
If capacity is constrained, ship lightweight version 1 artifacts for all three, but put deepest review and enforcement on the first item.
